<DocsLayout title="Routines & progression" description="Templates with rep targets, and the exact rules behind Forge's double-progression and deload suggestions.">
  <SectionHero section="training" />
  <h1>Routines &amp; progression</h1>
  <p>
    A routine is a template: exercises in order, target set counts, rep ranges, rest times,
    and superset links. Start a workout from one and the progression engine fills in what it
    thinks you should lift today. The rules are below — all of them.
  </p>
  <DocsMeta />

  <h2>Templates carry structure, history carries weights</h2>
  <p>
    Routines deliberately do not store weights. When you start a workout, each exercise pulls
    last session's sets as ghosts, and — when the routine sets a rep range — a computed
    suggestion. Weights are state, and the engine updates them every session; a weight frozen
    in a template would be wrong within three weeks.
  </p>

  <h2>Double progression, exactly</h2>
  <p>When a routine exercise has a rep range (say 6–10), starting a workout runs this check:</p>
  <ol>
    <li>Take every working set from your previous session of that exercise.</li>
    <li>If <strong>all</strong> of them hit the top of the rep range, suggest
      <em>last top weight + increment</em> (2.5 by default, configurable per exercise).</li>
    <li>Otherwise, no suggestion — finish filling out the range first.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>Deload detection, exactly</h2>
  <p>With <strong>Deload hints</strong> enabled in Settings, a second check runs when you have not progressed:</p>
  <ol>
    <li>Look at your last three sessions of the exercise.</li>
    <li>If all three share the same top weight and <strong>none</strong> of them completed the
      rep target on every set, the lift is stalled.</li>
    <li>The suggestion becomes ~90% of the stalled weight, rounded to your increment.</li>
  </ol>
  <p>
    The same detector feeds the <strong>Stalled lifts</strong> card on the stats page, so you
    hear about a stall on your sofa, not mid-set.
  </p>

  <Callout variant="note" title="Built-in plans">
    The Plans tab ships StrongLifts 5×5, Push/Pull/Legs, Upper/Lower and Full Body — one tap
    adopts them into your routines, rep ranges included, so progression works immediately.
  </Callout>
</DocsLayout>
